<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Insurance Sector Opens Further to Foreign Firms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401124094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1053 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 14 (XINHUA) -- China is considering 
the possibilities of allowing more overseas insurance companies 
to set up branches in coastal areas and special economic zones, 
official sources disclosed here today. 
  Under the plan, which has yet to be ratified by the State 
Council, overseas firms would be permitted to operate 
foreign-related insurance business in China. But they can only 
settle their accounts in foreign currencies. 
  The move represents China's bid to meet the challenge of 
restoring the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), as 
well as an endeavor to broaden international cooperation in the 
areas of insurance, a relatively weak sector in the country. 
  However, China will be cautious about the step. It would be 
a gradual process, the sources said, adding that conditions are 
not yet ripe for a large-scale opening up. 
  Some restrictions are expected with regard to branches to be 
established in China, the sources said, without giving further 
details. 
  Experts here said that opening up China's insurance sector 
will not only boost the country's insurance business, but help 
garner more foreign funds. 
  With a population of about 1.2 billion, China is a huge 
insurance market in the eyes of many foreign investors. In 
fact, more than 30 foreign insurance companies have set up 
representative offices and agencies in China so far, the 
majority of which are offering consulting services or acting as 
agents. 
  Over the years, the People's Insurance Company of China 
(PICC), China's flag-carrier in this field, has established good 
business ties with insurance firms in almost all countries and 
regions, according to Shi Guoqing, deputy general manager of 
PICC's International Department. 
  In line with the basic principle of "equality and mutual 
benefit" embodied in GATT, China will be given the opportunity 
of entering the international insurance market, while opening up 
its own. 
  PICC, which monopolises more than 90 percent of the 
country's 
total insurance business, is currently accelerating the pace for 
developing overseas insurance business. 
  China-funded insurance agencies are now scattered in Hong 
Kong, Macao, Singapore, Britain, the U.S., Germany and 
Luxembourg. They can conduct businesses such as property 
insurance, life insurance, re-insurance and in the fields of 
investment and securities. 
  The number of such agencies has risen to 71. A total of 
1,000 employees are working in the agencies, which witnessed a 
general insurance premium income of about 230 million U.S. 
dollars last year. 
  The Hong Kong Chinese Insurance Group Company (CIG), which 
was opened last year, has captured about 20 percent of the total 
business in Hong Kong insurance market. The Hong Kong Minan 
Insurance Company, a subsidiary of CIG, ranked first in the same 
trade in Hong Kong for its large premium income. 
  China-funded insurance companies in Macao also hold as much 
as 40 percent of the market. 
  As mentioned by Shi Guoqing, beside successfully organizing 
the CIG and European China Holdings Company last year, China 
will take a bolder step to set up regional management companies 
in Southeast Asia and in North America in the near future. 
  Then the country will try to knit a world-wide insurance 
network, so as to make China's insurance business more 
competitive on the world market. 
  Shi Guoqing said that there was a broad prospect for China 
to 
develop overseas insurance business, as the world market is a 
sizable one. Statistics show that the world's yearly premium 
income is about 1,400 billion U.S. dollars. 
  In the meantime, the PICC has also done well in developing 
foreign-related insurance business, which has contributed a lot 
to foreign trade, and improving the investment environment. 
  Last year, premium income for foreign-related insurance 
business achieved more than 700 million U.S. dollars, up 30 
percent over the previous year. 
  PICC has now opened 80-plus insurance items for 
foreign-related business, which include off-shore petroleum 
drilling, satellite-launching and construction of nuclear power 
plants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-45520 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi010_n_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-010 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

