<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Henan Province's Overseas Investment Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401074494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0651 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zhengzhou, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Central China's 
Henan Province has become attractive to overseas businessmen, as 
the number of foreign-funded enterprises approved in 1993 
surpassed the total in the previous 14 years. 
  According to a local official, last year 1,653 
foreign-funded 
enterprises were approved, with a promised investment of 1.55 
billion dollars, up 73 percent and 77 percent over 1992, 
respectively. 
  And ten projects financed with loans of foreign governments 
to the tune of a total of 519 million U.S. dollars started in 
1993. 
  As a result, a batch of medium and large state-owned 
enterprises have made great progress in their restructuring by 
utilizing foreign funds. 
  For example, the newly established Jiaozuo Xinda Chemical 
Company, financed with 10 million U.S. dollars by a chemical 
industry factory in Jiaozuo City and a Hong Kong firm, has 
become the largest ink powder producer in the world. 
  The official said the paid-in investment reached 376 million 
U.S. dollars in 1993, exceeding the total in the previous 14 
years. 

</TEXT>

