<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Coal Industry Production, Employment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1301121894 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1336 GMT 
12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1301121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 11 (CNS)--China's coal industry 
last year saw its output of raw coal reaching 1.14 billion 
tonnes, resulting in loss-making of RMB 2 billion less than the 
year before and with 120,000 staff made redundant. [paragraph as 
received] 
  Minister of Coal Industry, Mr Wang Senhao, said at a 
national 
working conference on coal production held here today that the 
output of raw coal in the country last year increased by 25.5 
million tonnes over the year before. State-owned enterprises 
turned out 470 million tonnes of coal, a drop of 12.5 million 
tonnes, resulting in a sales volume of 412 million tonnes, a 
drop of 19.49 million tonnes. The output of local state-owned 
enterprises was 198 million tonnes, down 4.3 million tonnes. 
  The volume of coal transportation made up 40 percent of the 
country's total volume of railway shipments and problems faced 
in shipping coal was one of the major factors accounting for the 
drop in coal production. Owing to the rising of prices, 
collectively-run coal mines and township ones saw their 
production last year accounting for 472 million tonnes, close to 
that produced by state- owned ones. 
  Last year, the coal industry made progress in the drop in 
loss- making and redundancy action with its loss being reduced 
by RMB 2 billion or 30 percent less than the previous year and 
120,000 staff made redundant while another 130,000 transferred 
to other jobs. 
  According to the minister, the industry has in recent years 
made achievements in its industrial adjustment, paying much 
attention to the development of its diversified interests. The 
industry has, besides coal production, business covering power 
generation, chemical industry, construction materials and 
commerce and trade. Its output earned from its diversified 
interests reached RMB 18 billion and its profits tax from this 
sector RMB 900 million, increase of 20 percent and 22 percent 
over the year before. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-45535 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi010_n_94030" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-010 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coal Consumer Debt Taxes Industry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1301120594 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1240 GMT 
12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1301120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 11 (CNS)--Coal consumers in China 
have run up a total debt of as much as RMB 19.1 billion, the 
Minister of Coal Industry, Mr Wang Senhao, revealed. He said 
that serious difficulties facing the coal industry last year lay 
in the large amount of debt owed by coal consumers with the 
money in arrears increasing by RMB 3.8 billion over late last 
year. 
  Such debt, according to Mr Wang, resulted in a serious 
shortage of capital required by the coal industry with the 
payroll for coalminers being badly affected. Banks had to help 
pay salaries by giving coal mines loans. 
  The shortage of capital needed by coal mines make them 
unable 
to afford raw and processed materials as well as equipment, all 
of which are of great importance to the safety of coal mine 
work. As important repairs for mine facilities cannot be 
carried out because of lack of money, safety technology required 
by the coal industry had been adversely affected. 
  Statistics show that orders accepted by coal enterprises 
registered a sharp drop last year, making up a mere one-tenth of 
orders received in 1992. Orders for coal mining equipment 
amounted to a mere RMB 93 million for 1994, far lower than the 
RMB 651 million in 1992. Facilities for safety in the coal 
industry cannot be renewed because of the shortage of capital. 
  Should the input into mining production not be forthcoming, 
according to the Vice Minister of Coal Industry, Mr Zhang 
Baoming, the supply of coal will be in jeopardy. 
  These serious problems have been of great concern to the 
State Council which decided to allocate a bank loan of RMB 1.5 
billion to the coal industry to pay salaries to the miners, Mr 
Wang said. The State Council was determined that the People's 
Bank of China and the Economic and Trade Commission would be 
responsible for the settling of the debt in the coal industry 
and a national meeting of heads of branches of the People's Bank 
of China would place it at the top of the agenda for an early 
solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

