<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reports Increase in Irrigated Area </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301051394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0327 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301051394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 13 (XINHUA) -- China managed to 
increase its irrigated area by more than 330,000 ha [hectare] in 
1993, according to the latest statistics from the Ministry of 
Water Resources. 
  In the first three years of the Eighth Five-Year Plan period 
(1991-1995) the country increased its irrigated area by 1.4 
million ha, accounting for 71 percent of the target set for the 
whole period. 
  For various reasons, the country's irrigated area decreased 
year by year during the Sixth Five-Year Plan period (1981-1985). 
But the decrease trend was brought under control during the 
following five years. Since 1991 the irrigated area has kept 
increasing. 
  By the end of 1993 the total irrigated area of the country 
had grown to 49.8 million ha from 16 million ha in the early 
1950s, showing an average annual increase rate of 2.6 percent. 
  Experts attributed the increase to the efforts of 
governments 
at various levels and the local people to build new and upgrade 
old water-control projects. 
  So far, one third of the country -- Hebei, Henan, Shandong, 
Anhui, Yunnan, Shaanxi, Gansu, Shanxi and Qinghai Provinces and 
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region -- has fulfilled the 
irrigated area increase targets for the 1991-1995 period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

