<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Interviews Sudanese Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<H4>   On Qian Qichen's Visit </H4>
<F P=102> OW1101203594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1942 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101203594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, January 11 (XINHUA) -- Sudanese Foreign 
Minister Husayn Abu-Salih stressed here today Chinese-Sudanese 
ties have registered considerable growth in various fields. 
  He described China as a strong supporter of the Third World 
countries in the United Nations. 
  The minister made these remarks in an interview with XINHUA 
before the visit to Sudan by Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen . 
  The Sudanese minister said that despite the reforms in both 
countries and changes on the regional and international arenas, 
the ties between the two countries follow a correct course of 
development. 
  This is due to their commitment to the five principles of 
peaceful coexistence in their foreign policies, he said. 
  The minister added that the visit to Sudan of the Chinese 
vice- premier constitutes a strong push to the relations between 
the two countries and is highly appreciated by Sudan. 
  Salih pointed out that Sino-Sudanese relations have a long 
history. The two countries established diplomatic relations in 
1959 and Sudan was one of the first countries backing China's 
admission into the United Nations. 
  In 1993, the two countries signed an economic, technical and 
commercial agreement covering a wider range of bilateral 
cooperation, he added. 
  The minister stressed Sudan will never forget the assistance 
China has rendered in the past. 
  The forthcoming visit to Sudan by the Chinese vice-premier 
will open new spheres for cooperation between the two friendly 
countries, he said. 
  During his stay in Sudan between January 13 and 15, the 
senior Chinese official will meet with a number of Sudan's 
prominent figures, including President of the Republic 'Umar 
Hasan Ahmad al- Bashir, and discuss with Sudanese officials 
bilateral, regional and international issues of common concern. 
He will also visit a number of enterprises initiated by China 
in Sudan. 

</TEXT>

