<H3> <TI>   U.S., Russian Foreign Ministers Draft Agreements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301125994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1231 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 13 (XINHUA) -- While U.S. and 
Russian presidents were holding their first round of talks this 
morning, their foreign minister and secretary of state prepared 
a package of draft agreements due to be signed by the two 
leaders. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and U.S. secretary 
of 
state Warren Christopher held close-door meeting in the Yellow 
Hall of the Kremlin to complete the documents today 
  Among the major documents to be signed are the Moscow 
Declaration on the Outcome of the Clinton Visit, a memorandum on 
cooperation in export controls, and a joint statement on the 
Middle-East peace process, according to official sources here. 
  The two foreign ministers also discussed the result of the 
NATO summit held earlier this week in Brussels. 
  Kozyrev said the U.S. Partnership for Peace Proposal, 
adopted 
by the NATO summit, "suits Russia well," and that Russia 
considers it capable of leading to large-scale cooperation among 
all countries "interested in it." 

</TEXT>

